SIMPLE: gladness
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gladness
<hw>Glad"ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>gl⟦ae⟧dnes</ets>.]</ety> <def>State or quality of being glad;
pleasure; joyful satisfaction; cheerfulness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They . . . did eat their meat with <qex>gladness</qex> and
singleness of heart.</q> <rj><qau>Acts ii. 46.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Gladness</xex> is rarely or never equivalent to
<xex>mirth</xex>, <xex>merriment</xex>, <xex>gayety</xex>, and
<xex>triumph</xex>, and it usually expresses less than
<xex>delight</xex>. It sometimes expresses great joy.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Jews had joy and <qex>gladness</qex>, a feast and a good
day.</q> <rj><qau>Esther viii. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gladship</ent>⟦br⟧
